The Independent Police Investigative Directorate (Ipid) is probing how a Nigerian man died immediately after being arrested by police last week.Tochukwu Nnadi died at the Grand Parade in Cape Town after allegedly being choked while lying on the ground handcuffed.Western Cape police spokesperson Andre Traut yesterday declined to comment on the case, saying it was being handled by Ipid.Ipid spokesperson Moses Dlamini was yet to confirm the investigation yesterday.It is alleged that Nnadi was arrested for drug dealing and later died after swallowing the drugs. But those who witnessed the incident have disputed the police s account arguing that the Nigerian was killed while handcuffed.President of the Nigerian Union in the Western Cape Rapuluchukwu Ufochukwu said that members of the metro police handcuffed and strangled Nnadi until he died.He said police brutality towards Nigerians in the country was rife. Activists have called for a through investigation into the man s death.African Diaspora Forum spokesperson Johson Emeka yesterday said: This is not the first case of a Nigerian being killed in South Africa. Another man was recently killed in Cape Town. They alleged that he had drugs and resisted arrest, but he was killed while handcuffed. Emeka said that Ipid should release its findings after completing its probe. They need to make those findings public. There has been a number of migrants, especially Nigerians who have died similar deaths and no one was held liable for their deaths, he said.Nigerian media quoted senior special assistant to President Muhammadu Buhari on Foreign Affairs and Diaspora Abike Dabuiri Erewa saying that 20 Nigerians had been killed in South Africa in 2016. Dabuiri Erewa said that the government should ensure that those responsible for the man s death were brought to book.ZODIDI MHLANAzodidim@thenewage.co.za